John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Independent schools in Scotland maintain academic excellence and this continued in 2018 with another set of outstanding exam results, which is only enhanced by individual and group success in sports, art, music and other community endeavors.
With more than 30,000 students everywhere in Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best service to their students and parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their students for further and higher education, the career they have chosen and their place as global citizens.
As an educational center that can design and implement tailored school programs, we see that modern languages continue to be popular and desired as an elective subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, it will make him scornful.
If you speak to him in his own language, it will strike him in the soul.”
This is a strong reminder that we cannot rely only on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From this year’s recent exam results, we can see that languages outperform all other subjects with the highest success rates in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages achieved a higher score of “5+”.
Data collected from 74 SCIS schools showed that 72 percent of students achieved a higher "5+" score in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those who learned German, 69 percent of those who learned French, and 63 percent of those who learned Spanish also achieved a "5".
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will undoubtedly acquire in the future.
Languages now, as an elective subject, are seen at the same level as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering, and mathematics) in independent school programs, as elsewhere.
A 2014 survey by the UK’s Employment and Skills Commission found that 17 percent of the reasons employers cited them as failing to fill jobs were due to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly imperative in order to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more and more jobs requiring languages, these skills are indispensable in a globalized world.
No matter which career one chooses, if they have learned a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future with such a lifelong skill.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will automatically give the polyglot an advantage over the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 U.K. adults in 2013, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to speak, and French was the only language spoken by over 10 percent, i.e. 15 percent of people.
Therefore, investing in language teaching is now important for today’s children.
Having multiple languages, especially those of developing economies, will equip children with better chances of finding meaningful employment.
In Scotland, each school will differ according to the languages it teaches.
Several schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages considered the most important in the UK when looking into the future by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
No matter what the interests of your child are, there will always be a number of languages to choose from in independent schools, with professors who are specialists in this field.
Scottish Independent Schools are committed to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills needed to succeed, no matter what the future may bring.
At present, it cannot be denied, in the global business environment, that languages will continue to be vital to the country’s future, so this must be replicated in schools.
In fact, modern languages should really be considered as “international communication skills”.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to the young people of Scotland.
"Il faut bien le faire" (it must be done).
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
