North Korea Says 'No Chance' to Disarm Unilaterally Without Confidence
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that prolonged sanctions deepened distrust in the United States and there was no chance the country would unilaterally give up nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly of the world body that North Korea had taken "significant goodwill measures" last year, such as halting nuclear missile tests, dismantling nuclear test sites and committing itself against the proliferation of nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"However, we do not see an appropriate response from the United States," he said.
“Without trust in the United States, there will be no trust in our national security, and under such conditions, there is no way to unilaterally disarm ourselves first.”
While Ri reiterated North Korea’s well-known complaints about Washington’s resistance to accessing nuclear disarmament “in stages,” according to which North Korea would be gradually rewarded for the steps taken, his statement seemed significant because he did not reject unilateral, nuclear disarmament, without discussion, as Pyongyang has done.
Ree alluded to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit in general of the current US president and North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work towards “nuclear disarmament of the Korean peninsula” while Trump gave a guarantee of North Korea’s security.
North Korea demands a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States insists Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington also refuses to yield to tough international sanctions on North Korea.
"The United States insists on 'nuclear disarmament first and foremost' and increases the level of pressure with sanctions to achieve its goal by coercion, and even opposes the 'declaration of an end to the war,'" Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a vain dream for people who don’t know us.
But the problem is that the existing sanctions deepen our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the US leader stressed at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister stressed the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If South Korea were the other side of this nuclear disarmament issue, instead of the United States, nuclear disarmament on the Korean peninsula would not have ended in such a dead end.”
However, Ri’s tone of speech was significantly different from last year’s when he told the U.N. General Assembly that directing North Korean missiles to the U.S. mainland was inevitable after “Mr. Evil President” Trump called Kim a “missile” on a suicide mission.
At the United Nations this year, Trump, who last year threatened to "completely destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his courage to take steps to disarm, but said much remained to be done and that sanctions must remain until North Korea's nuclear disarmament.
On Wednesday, Trump said he didn’t have a timeframe for that, saying “whether it takes two years, three years or five months – it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia believe that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps taken.
However, U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that "Security Council sanctions must continue fully and without exception until complete, definitive nuclear disarmament is confirmed."
The Security Council has unanimously increased sanctions on North Korea since 2006 to obstruct funding for Pyongyang’s nuclear weapons and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met Ri on the sidelines of the U.N. General Assembly and then said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare a second summit.
