Harvard students take courses to get enough rest.
A new course at Harvard University this year aims to teach all graduates more sleep in order to combat the growing macho-culture of learning by staying up all night with the help of caffeine.
One researcher found that students at the world’s leading university often don’t know anything when it comes to basic self-care.
Charles Chaizler, a professor of dream medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham Women's Hospital, designed the course he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after giving a speech about the impact of insufficient sleep on learning.
“At the end of the lecture, a girl came to me and said, ‘Why are you telling me this now, in the last year?’
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep - which surprised me," he told Telegraph.
The course, which was offered for the first time this year, explains to students the basics of how good sleep habits help in academic and athletic performance, while also improving overall well-being.
Paul Barrera, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of health services at the university, said the university had decided to introduce the course after discovering that students had a serious lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one part, there is a picture of a dormitory where students press on coffee cups, curtains, sneakers and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light and how not enough sleep affects athletic performance and the importance of bedtime routine.
In another section, participants learn about how long-term lack of sleep can increase the risk of heart attacks and strokes, depression and cancer.
A campus map, with interactive icons, then encourages participants to reflect on their daily routine.
“We know that it will not change the behavior of students immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know – just as you have a right to know about the health effects when you choose to smoke a cigarette.”
The culture of pride in “working all night” still exists, he said, and besides, modern technology and increasing pressure on students mean that lack of sleep is a growing problem.
Having enough sleep, of good quality, should be the student's "secret weapon" in the fight against stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said - even to avoid obesity, because lack of sleep causes the brain to go into starvation mode, which makes them constantly hungry.
Raymond Sow, a 19-year-old California student of chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Chaizler design the course after attending one of his classes last year, in his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to act for a course throughout the student city.
He hopes that the next step is to ask all postgraduates to complete a similar program before joining a competitive institution.
Professor Chaizler recommended that students consider setting an alarm about when to go to bed, and when to wake up and be aware of the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted from electronic screens and LED light, which displaces the circadian rhythm, leading to problems with falling asleep.
