He said: “Until this day, those feelings of inferiority and diversity have been the things that gave me the power and strength to succeed.”
He wanted to prove that he was “something,” he said, so as not to disappoint everyone when they finally find out about his sexuality.
The two-bronze medal-winning Olympian became a prominent supporter of LGBT campaigns and used his performance at this year's Commonwealth Games in Australia to appeal to more countries to decriminalize homosexuality.
He said he spoke publicly because he felt happy to be able to live openly without division and to give “hope” to others.
The three-time world champion said about falling in love with a man - American filmmaker Dustin Lance Black, who met him in 2013 - "surprised me".
Daley married the Oscar-winning actor, who is 20 years old, last year, but said the age difference was never a problem.
"When you go through so much at an early age" - he went to the first Olympics at the age of 14, and his father died of cancer three years later - he said it was difficult to find someone of the same age who had experienced similar heights and depths.
