New German Navy Ship Delayed Again
The German Navy’s latest frigate was due to be delivered in 2014 to replace Cold War-era antiquated warships, but it won’t happen until at least next year due to faulty systems and rising prices, local media reported.
The delivery of the Rheinland-Falz, the flagship of the new class of Baden-Wittemberg frigates, has now been postponed to the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Di Zeit, citing a military spokesman.
The ship was due to join the Navy in 2014, but problematic issues after delivery hampered the fate of the ambitious project.
The four Baden-Wittemberg-class ships ordered by the Navy in 2007 will be a replacement for the obsolete Bremen-class frigates.
It is known that they will contain a powerful cannon, a large number of anti-aircraft weapons and naval missiles, as well as some stealth technology, such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic trace.
Among other important features is less maintenance - it should be possible, the latest frigates, to be absent for up to two years from domestic ports.
However, the constant delays mean that modern warships – which should allow Germany to have power across the oceans – will be obsolete by the time they enter service.
The frigate with the unfortunate fate of the F125 reached the headlines last year when the German navy officially refused to receive the ship and returned it to the Blom and Vos shipyards in Hamburg.
It was the first time the Navy had returned a ship to a shipbuilder after delivery.
Little is known about the reasons for the return, but German media cited a number of key "software and hardware defects" that made the warship useless if sent on a combat mission.
The software flaws were particularly important because the Baden-Wittemberg-class ships would have a crew of about 120 sailors – only half the crew of the older Bremen-class frigates.
It also turned out that the ship was drastically above the planned weight, which reduces its performance and limits the Navy's ability to add upgrades in the future.
The Rhineland-Palatinate weighs 7,000 tons and is believed to be twice as heavy as the similar class of ships used by Germany in World War II.
In addition to problematic hardware, the cost of the entire project – including crew training – has also become a problem.
It is said to have reached an incredible <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>3.1 billion ($3.6 billion) – an increase from the initial <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2.2 billion.
The problems facing the latest frigates are particularly important because of warnings of Germany's reduced naval power.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the defence commission of the German parliament, confirmed that the navy is "lacking ships that can be deployed".
The representative said the problem has worsened over time, as old ships have been withdrawn from service, but no replacement ships have been provided.
He complained that none of the Baden-Wittemberg-class frigates could join the Navy.
The National Trust is listening to the secret life of bats
A new property survey is underway in Scotland’s mountainous regions to find out how bats use the area in their search for food.
There is hope that the findings will provide answers to the behavior of unique flying mammals and help guide conservation activities in the future.
The study by scientists at the National Trust for Scotland will follow common and soprano bats, as well as long-eared brown bats and daubenton bats at Inverrow Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special shooters will be placed in key locations around the property to monitor bat activity during the season.
N.H.S. personnel and volunteers will also carry mobile research using handheld detectors.
Expert analyses of sounds from all recordings will determine the frequency depending on the type of bats.
Then a map of the habitats will be drawn up to create a detailed picture of their behavior in the area.
Rob Dewar, a conservation adviser at N.T.S., hopes the results will reveal which areas of life are most important to bats and how each species uses them.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management, such as the creation of meadows and how best to maintain forests for bats and other related species.
The population of bats in Scotland and Britain has declined significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development that affect beds and habitat loss.
Windmills and lights also pose a risk, as do fly adhesive tapes and some chemical treatments for building materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats.
Bats aren't actually blind.
However, due to their hunting habits at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use sophisticated echo-location techniques to find insects and obstacles in the flight path.
N.T.S., which cares for more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the state, takes bats very seriously.
There are ten trained experts who regularly conduct research, bed inspections, and sometimes rescues.
The organization even established the first and only bat reserve in Scotland on the Triv estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of the ten species that live in Scotland.
Property manager David Thomson says the property is ideal territory for them.
"We have a great area for bats here in Triv," he said.
“We have old buildings, very old two and very good living quarters.
But there are a lot of unknown things about bats, so the work we do here and on other properties will help us learn more about what they need to thrive.”
He stressed that it is important to check if there are bats before property renovations are carried out because the unconscious destruction of litters can destroy up to 400 females and cubs, and destroy the entire local population.
The bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, torture or disturb or destroy their beds.
Elizabeth Ferrell, a Scottish clerk at the Bat Protection Trust, encourages the public to help.
She said, “We still have a lot to learn about bats and our other species, we just don’t know how they live.”
