Brexit: Britain 'will always regret' losing car manufacturers
Britain will “always regret” if it loses its status as a world leader in car production after Brexit, Business Secretary Greg Clark said on Monday.
He added that it was "concerning" that Toyota-Britain told the BBC that if Britain left the EU without a deal, it would temporarily stop production at a plant in Burnaston, near Derby.
"We need a deal," Mr. Clark said.
The Japanese automaker said the impact of border lockdowns in the event of a no-deal Brexit would cost jobs.
The plant in Burnaston – which produces Toyota Auris and Avensis – produced nearly 150,000 cars last year, 90% of which were exported to the rest of the European Union.
"In my opinion, if the UK leaves the EU at the end of March, there will be a cessation of production at our factory," said Marvin Cook, Toyota's managing director in Burnaston.
Other carmakers in the UK have expressed concern about how cross-border trade will work if they leave the EU without a deal, including Honda, Be-M-We and Jaguar Land Rover.
Be-M-We, for example, says it will close its mini-factory in Oxford one month after Brexit.
The main concerns are related to what car manufacturers call the risks of the logistics chain in the case of a no-deal Brexit.
Toyota’s production line operates on a “just-in-time” system, with parts arriving every 37 minutes from suppliers in the UK and EU, for cars as ordered.
If Britain leaves the EU without a deal on March 29, there could be a border break that industry says could cause delays and gaps in parts.
It will be impossible for Toyota to store more than a daily supply of inventory at the Derbyshire plant, the company said, so production will stop.
Mr Clark said Theresa May's plan for future relations with the EU was "precisely designed to avoid such border checks".
"We need to have a deal. We need to have the best deal that will allow us not only to succeed in the present, but to seize this opportunity," he told the BBC's Radio 4 program today.
“The evidence not only from Toyota but also from other manufacturers is that we must be able to continue what is a very successful set of logistics chains.”
Toyota could not say how long production would be halted, but warned in the long run that the additional costs would reduce the plant’s competitiveness and cost jobs.
Peter Cuvalaris, who has been working at Burnston for 24 years and is a union representative at the factory, said that its members are becoming increasingly concerned: “According to my experience, once those jobs are gone, they will never return.
According to a government spokesman, "We have drawn up a precise and credible plan for our future relationship with the EU."
