New information on red tide: Concentrations are decreasing in Pinelas, Manati and Sarasota
A recent report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general decline in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the Commission, conditions of uneven algae blooming have been observed in the area of Pinellas, Manati, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, indicating a decrease in concentrations.
The red tide, a consequence of the blooming of red algae, extends about 130 miles off the coast from North Pinelas County to South Lee County.
Parts of the red tide can also be seen about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but the number is still lower compared to last week.
Red tide has also been observed in Pasco County.
During the past week, the following concentrations have been observed: mean concentrations in or on the Coley County coastline, low to high concentrations on the Hillsborough County coastline, common to high concentrations in or on the Sarasota County coastline, common to medium concentrations in the Charlotte County coastline, common to high concentrations in the Charlotte County coastline.
Cases of respiratory irritation continue to occur in Pinelas, Manati, Sarasota, Lee, and Collier counties.
No cases of respiratory irritation have been reported in Northwest Florida during the past week.
